"...Jumpstarting Mary Shelley's corpses is the least of our problems; something much along that line happens in intensive-care wards every day.

Human thought itself, in its unprecedented guise as computer software, is becoming something to be crystallized, replicated, made a commodity. Even the insides of our brains aren't sacred; on the contrary, the human brain is a primary target of increasingly successful research, ontological and spiritual questions be damned. The idea that, under these circumstances, Human Nature is somehow destined to prevail against the Great Machine, is simply silly; it seems weirdly beside the point. It's as if a rodent philosopher in a lab-cage, about to have his brain bored and wired for the edification of Big Science, were to piously declare that in the end Rodent Nature must triumph.

Anything that can be done to a rat can be done to a human being. And we can do most anything to rats. This is a hard thing to think about, but it's the truth. It won't go away because we cover our eyes. *This* is cyberpunk." This is a quote from Bruce Sterling, one of the group of authors who created cyberpunk about 40 years ago.

Anonymous Sun 13 Jan 2019 13:57:34 No.20623211 Report

>>20622364
No. You're not overthinking it. For engaging plot you have to follow the rules of your own universe constantly or you lose immersion by your audience. Yes, it is possible to overthink it, but you're not that far out there yet.

You can still use other drugs, teas, herbs and foods. Open your thinking up to more general interactions and items in the universe you create. You seem to be stuck on alcohol and trying to force a square peg into a round hole. Look for a round peg. Another example: fish & reptiles can have a hard time digesting fat-rich food. Due to lower body temperature, it solidifies and can clog up their digestive tract and their blood circulation. Mammals are warm enough they can consume & digest certain fats (especially animal) and still maintain them in more fluid form.

Your lizard girl maybe eats the wrong food, a fat-heavy stew prepared by humans that burn it with their metabolism as the high-energy food source it is in cold weather. Lizards would do better with a vegetable fat (such as olive oil, nuts) to get energy, and it remains more fluid at slightly lower body temps.

She can safely consume very small amounts of alcohol, like spacing a half shot glass out once every 2 or 3 hours, and get sustainable energy from it. Natural sugars, such as honey, used in moderation, can be another solution.

What you are trying to solve is a metabolism problem. She is designed to hibernate in cold weather. Maybe she needs to sleep through the winter. Or, change her metabolism to that of a dinosaur (or, as we call them today, birds). They were warm-blooded, not reptiles. Their metabolism is closer to human. She maybe more stiff in the cold than humans, but with dino metabolism it wouldn't be as crippling. And animal fat & alcohol would be less lethal.

Yeah. She needs to bundle up with insulation to preserve what body heat she has. That would include her tail, which acts as a radiator to lose heat in a desert, opposite of what's needed in the North.

>>20625514
>hugging to a hot water bottles
Remember that water is heavy, and once it cools below a certain temperature, then it drags your average core temp toward whatever temp it's at.

Apart from those concerns, water does have some good uses. It holds heat better than over 90% of every other substance on Earth. Cheap & common. If she has the time for it, while she's in shelter she can bundle up with the warmest water bottles she can tolerate, bringing her core temp up and warming the inside of her clothing. Then, just as she goes out the door, she can switch for new bottles freshly hot. They will cool more slowly and she'll start out with a high, well-insulated core temp and maximize her outside time before it starts becoming too dangerous. She can also drink as much warm water as she can tolerate just before walking out the door to further increase this efficiency a little bit.

As long as she's physically active, especially when starting from a high core temp, her metabolism will generate good heat and further extend her excursion time. Her greatest danger will be forced inactivity. So, chopping wood outside and she gets much more time, but sitting in an ambush blind while hunting gives her the shortest time.

Don't know the tech level of your world, but there are chemical heating devices that can be invented. Mix two dry chemicals and they can generate low grade, constant heat for 18 to 24 hours. They are vastly lighter weight than water, but in our Real world, the best tech advances for this solution have only been developed & implemented in the past 30 years or so with a fairly radical leap forward since about 2000.

If you're sticking with reptile metabolism, research what foods different reptiles eat for their energy & nutrition requirements. That should help you imagine solutions. Different species of reptiles have developed different diets for reasons of opportunity and evolutionary niche.
